# Area Population Workflow

Use this workflow when an area's memory files are empty stubs or missing content.
An area is "unseeded" if `MEMORY.md` contains no summaries, or typed files have only placeholder text.

## When to Use

Trigger this workflow when:
- A team member says "this area has no context yet"
- You open an area's files and they are mostly blank
- `MEMORY.md` shows all files as "not yet populated"

## Step 1 — Discover Existing Sources

Query available data sources for content about this area:

1. **Sana** — search meeting notes for the area name and related terms
2. **NotebookLM** — check if a notebook exists for this area or team
3. **Project tracking** (Jira, Linear, GitHub Issues) — search for epics and stories
4. **Communication** (Slack, Teams) — search channels relevant to this area
5. **Docs** (Notion, Confluence, Google Drive) — find relevant pages or folders

Note which sources are available and which returned useful content.
If a source is unavailable, skip it and note it in your summary.

## Step 2 — Draft Memory Files

Using the discovered content, draft all 4 typed files:

### `user.md` — draft format
```markdown
# User Context — {area}

## Area Owner
[Name and role — from configured sources, CODEOWNERS, or shared context]

## Domain Knowledge
[What the team member knows well about this area]

## Preferences
[How the user likes to work in this area]

## Key Stakeholders
[Eng lead, design, GTM, CS contacts]
```

### `project.md` — draft format
```markdown
# Project Context — {area}

## Active Initiatives
[Current in-flight work — from Jira epics or configured sources]

## Recent Decisions
[Key decisions made in the last quarter — from meeting notes]

## Upcoming Deadlines
[Dates and deliverables — from Jira or project.md in shared/]

## Blockers
[Known blockers or dependencies]
```

### `feedback.md` — draft format
```markdown
# Feedback & Agent Guidance — {area}

## What Has Worked
[Approaches that were effective in past sessions]

## What Hasn't Worked
[Approaches to avoid]

## User Feedback Themes
[Top themes from configured feedback sources]

## Agent Notes
[Guidance for future sessions in this area]
```

### `reference.md` — draft format
```markdown
# Reference — {area}

## Jira Filters
[Saved filters or JQL queries for this area]

## Analytics Events
[Key events to track — names and event IDs]

## Queries
[Useful data queries for this area]

## Feature Flags
[Feature flags related to this area]

## Dashboards
[Links to dashboards or reporting tools]

## External Links
[Issue trackers, design files, specs]
```

## Step 3 — Show Drafts to User

Present all 4 drafted files to the user:

```
I've drafted memory files for {area} using:
- [sources used]

Here are the drafts:

[paste each file content]

Does this look accurate? What should I change before I write these?
```

## Step 4 — Revise and Write

1. Make any changes the user requests
2. Ask once more: "Ready to write these to memory/{path}/?"
3. Only write after explicit user confirmation
4. After writing, update `MEMORY.md` with one-line summaries of each file

## Step 5 — Update MEMORY.md

After writing all 4 files, update `MEMORY.md`:

```markdown
# Memory Index — {area}

## user.md
[one-line summary]

## project.md
[one-line summary]

## feedback.md
[one-line summary]

## reference.md
[one-line summary]

Last populated: {date}
Sources used: {list}
```

## Critical Rules

- Never write draft content without user review
- Note all sources used (so they can be verified or updated later)
- If a source was unavailable, leave the relevant section blank with a note: `[not yet populated — source unavailable]`
- Population is a one-time setup; normal session updates go through Phase 5 — Capture
